
This is a (reasonably) portable and lightweight software Connector for the EBYTE
E22 series (E22xxxTxxU/D) Lora devices, supporting the USB module (Linux) and
DIP module (Linux/ESP32) variants.

It has been tested, and is in use with, E22-900T22U (USB), E22-900T22D (DIP) and
E22-900T30D (DIP) versions and it should work for the entire series: 230, 400
and 900 frequency and 20, 22, 30 and 33 dbm (max) power variants. Specifications
for the devices are in the specs directory.

In the family are also the EBYTE E220 and E32 series. The E22 is the newer and
more featured product, compared to the E220 and E32, which should also work with
this Connector with some minor changes (the E220 lacks the NETID configuration
field, making it one byte shorter). E220 and E32 lack repeater functionality.
E32 also lacks RSSI. The E22 is based on the new Semtech SX1262, and E220 on the
older Semtech SX1276. E32 is based on "low cost" Semtech LLCC68.

More information on the family at https://www.cdebyte.com/Module-SPISOCUART-SX12.

The Linux build includes command line testers for USB and DIP (requires libgpiod)
and a 'tomqtt' version with udev and systemd configuration files (requires
mosquitto-dev).

The ESP32 build has been tested under Arduino IDE and Platform IO both using the
Arduino framework, and also under native ESP-IDF.

For USB, the device identifies as a CH340 serial interface (1a86:7523) and the
udev rules populate it as /dev/e22900t22u. The Connector enables the "Software
Mode Switching" setting to read/write configuration and product information.
This setting is disabled by default and therefore upon first use of the device,
the "touch switch" needs to be held for more than 1.5s to force the device into
configuration mode before the Connector starts, at which point it will then
enable and persist the setting so that no further manual intervention is
required.

For DIP, it is wired to the expansion header on Pi at 3V3 TTL levels. The Pi
needs "serial-console" to be disabled. Note that the 30 dbm versions do run at
3V3 but are recommended to use 5V0 to achieve full TX power: if doing so, and
using Pi's 5V0, the GPIO logic levels may need be level shifted (at least, the
input levels: the output levels from the Pi may be sufficient).

(Pi → E22 DIP)
  VCC  → 3.3V (Pin 1)
  GND  → GND  (Pin 6)
  TXD  → GPIO 15 / RXD (Pin 10)
  RXD  → GPIO 14 / TXD (Pin 8)
  M0   → GPIO 17 (Pin 11)
  M1   → GPIO 27 (Pin 13)
  AUX  → GPIO 22 (Pin 15)

This is a greenfield implementation, not based upon any others. 

